SIMPLE: individual
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Individual
<hw>In`di*vid"u*al</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>individuus</ets> indivisible; pref. <ets>in-</ets> not +
<ets>dividuus</ets> divisible, fr. <ets>dividere</ets> to divide: cf. F.
<ets>individuel</ets>. See <er>Divide</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Not divided, or not to be divided; existing as one
entity, or distinct being or object; single; one; <as>as, an
<ex>individual</ex> man, animal, or city</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mind has a being of its own, distinct from that of all other
things, and is pure, unmingled, <qex>individual</qex> substance.</q>
<rj><qau>A. Tucker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>United as one <qex>individual</qex> soul.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to one only; peculiar to, or
characteristic of, a single person or thing; distinctive; <as>as,
<ex>individual</ex> traits of character; <ex>individual</ex> exertions;
<ex>individual</ex> peculiarities.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Individual</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Individual
<hw>In`di*vid"u*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A single person,
animal, or thing of any kind; a thing or being incapable of separation
or division, without losing its identity; especially, a human being; a
person.</def> <rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An object which is in the strict and primary sense one, and can
not be logically divided, is called an <qex>individual</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Whately.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That <qex>individuals</qex> die, his will ordains.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An independent, or
partially independent, zooid of a compound animal.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>The product of a single egg, whether it remains a single animal or
becomes compound by budding or fission.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>individualise</ent>⟦br⟧
